  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Hebron",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] One of the most ancient cities in the world (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 13:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). When Abraham entered Canaan it was already existing under the name of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Kirjath Arba",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In its neighbourhood he often sojourned, and there he bought the cave of Machpelah from Ephron the Hittite for a family sepulchre for himself and his posterity (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 23:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ff.). On the conquest of Canaan it became the inheritance of Caleb (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 14:13-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and was made a priestly settlement and a city of refuge (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 21:11-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It was soon to attain greater importance as the capital of David’s kingdom during the first seven years and a half of his reign. It lies 20 miles south of Jerusalem, picturesquely situated in a narrow valley surrounded by rocky hills, whose sides are clothed with luxuriant vineyards. Its modern name is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "El Khulîl",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " = “The Friend,” in memory of Abraham who was called “the friend of God” (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 20:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 41:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "James 2:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "all the places",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", &c.] It is evident that David’s outlaw life must have lasted for some considerable time, and have proved an important factor in preparing the men of Judah to welcome him as their king. The instances quoted above indicate that it was during this period that he gained many of the faithful friends who afterwards filled offices of trust in his kingdom.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 31.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Hebron",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", destined soon to become David's capital (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 2:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), lay about fourteen miles south of Jerusalem. For an account of it see Conder, 'Tent Work,' 2:79, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "sqq.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " In comparing the list of David's heroes (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 11:26-47",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") with this catalogue of friendly towns, it will be found that several of them came from them, and had probably shared his exile at Ziklag. Such were Ira and Gareb, Ithrites from Jattir, Shama and Jehiel from Aroer; perhaps also Zabdi the Shiphmite (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 27:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") came from Siphmoth. We find David in this narrative acting justly as a soldier, generously to those who had been kind to him in his wanderings, and forming friendships which he retained and cherished long afterwards, when from being a fugitive he had become a king. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " 1 Samuel 30:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Hormah in the Negeb (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") is Zephath, the present Zepta, on the western slope of the Rakhma plateau (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 12:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Cor-ashan, probably the same place as Ashan in the shephelah, upon the border of the Negeb, has not yet been discovered (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:42",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Athach is only mentioned here, and quite unknown. According to Thenius, it is probably a mistaken spelling for Ether in the tribe of Simeon (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 19:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:43",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Hebron, the present el Khulil, Abraham's city (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 10:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 23:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
